# Security

## Always

- Use npm official registry; prefer viem / wagmi / RainbowKit for wallet integration.
- Validate address, chain, amount, and decimals — frontend checks are UX only; trust on-chain or server validation.
- Escape user-generated content; use HTTPS for APIs.
- Handle wallet rejection gracefully.
- Use WalletConnect / Reown Project IDs from official console; document purpose in comments or README.
- Keep signing and contract changes minimal and reviewable.

## Never

- Trust frontend validation alone for security boundaries.
- Use `innerHTML` or `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`.
- Log private keys, mnemonics, signatures, JWTs, or API secrets.
- Expose `.env` / `.env.local` in git or client bundles.
- Install unmaintained or unknown wallet SDKs; suggest `curl | bash`, random executables, or unofficial browser extensions.
- Integrate unknown third-party protocols without official documentation.
